[{"id":40177,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>600</mn></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>70</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>,&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>Angular speed of coil is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>500</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Instantaneous emf in coil is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>N</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>, where, magnetic flux&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;is angle between&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>.</p><p>So,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>N</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>N</mi><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></math></p><p>Putting the values, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>600</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>70</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>100</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mn>6</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>44</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40252,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mathrm{VR}_1 \\mathrm{R}_2}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{R}_1^2+\\mathrm{R}_2^2}}$ at $\\mathrm{t}=0$ and $\\frac{\\mathrm{V}}{\\mathrm{R}_2}$ at $\\mathrm{t}=\\infty$","$\\frac{V}{R_2}$ at $t=0$ and $\\frac{V\\left(R_1+R_2\\right)}{R_1 R_2}$ at $t=\\infty$","$\\frac{V}{R_2}$ at $t=0$ and $\\frac{V R_1 R_2}{\\sqrt{R_1^2+R_2^2}}$ at $t=\\infty$","$\\frac{V\\left(R_1+R_2\\right)}{R_1 R_2}$ at $t=0$ and $\\frac{V}{R_2}$ at $t=\\infty$"],"answer":1,"solution":"At $\\mathrm{t}=0$, inductor behaves like an infinite resistance\nSo at $t=0, i=\\frac{V}{R_2}$ and at $t=\\infty$, inductor behaves like a conducting wire\n$$\n\\mathrm{i}=\\frac{\\mathrm{V}}{\\mathrm{R}_{\\text {eq }}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{V}\\left(\\mathrm{R}_1+\\mathrm{R}_2\\right)}{\\mathrm{R}_1 \\mathrm{R}_2}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":40197,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>N</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo></math>and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>07</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>The maximum emf generated is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>&#969;</mi></math>,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>07</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>140</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></math></p><p>Thus, maximum emf is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>439</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>440</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40124,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$2\\sqrt{2} \\, \\dfrac{\\mu_0 L^2}{R}$","$\\sqrt{2} \\, \\dfrac{\\mu_0 L^2}{R}$","$\\sqrt{2} \\, \\dfrac{\\mu_0 R^2}{L}$","$2\\sqrt{2} \\, \\dfrac{\\mu_0 R^2}{L}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Using the reciprocity theorem, assume a current $I$ flows through the larger square loop and compute the flux through the smaller circular loop. The mutual inductance is given by $M = \\dfrac{\\Phi}{I}$.<br><br>Magnetic field at the centre of the square loop:<br>For a square of side $L$, the perpendicular distance from the centre to any side is $d = \\dfrac{L}{2}$, and each side subtends angles $\\theta_1 = \\theta_2 = 45^\\circ$ at the centre.<br><br>The field due to one finite straight segment is:<br>$B_{\\text{segment}} = \\dfrac{\\mu_0 I}{4\\pi d}(\\sin\\theta_1 + \\sin\\theta_2)$<br><br>$B_{\\text{segment}} = \\dfrac{\\mu_0 I}{4\\pi \\cdot \\frac{L}{2}}\\left(\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} + \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\right) = \\dfrac{\\mu_0 I}{2\\pi L} \\cdot \\sqrt{2} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 I}{2\\pi L}$<br><br>All four sides contribute equally in the same direction at the centre, so:<br>$B_{\\text{total}} = 4 \\cdot \\dfrac{\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 I}{2\\pi L} = \\dfrac{2\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 I}{\\pi L}$<br><br>Flux through the circular loop:<br>Since $L \\gg R$, the field $B_{\\text{total}}$ can be treated as uniform over the area $A = \\pi R^2$ of the circular loop.<br><br>$\\Phi = B_{\\text{total}} \\cdot A = \\dfrac{2\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 I}{\\pi L} \\cdot \\pi R^2 = \\dfrac{2\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 R^2 I}{L}$<br><br>Mutual inductance:<br>$M = \\dfrac{\\Phi}{I} = \\dfrac{2\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 R^2}{L}$<br><br>Hence, the correct option is $(4)\\ \\dfrac{2\\sqrt{2}\\,\\mu_0 R^2}{L}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40148,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$4 \\mathrm{mH}$","$1 \\mathrm{mH}$","$5 \\mathrm{mH}$","$2.5 \\mathrm{mH}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$(E m f)_{\\text {induced }}=-L \\frac{d i}{d t}$<br />In magnitude form,\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\left|\\operatorname{Emf}_{\\text {ind }}\\right|=\\left|(-) L \\frac{\\mathrm{di}}{\\mathrm{dt}}\\right| \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow 0.1=\\frac{(\\mathrm{L})[+2-(-2)]}{0.2} \\\\\n& \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{L}=\\frac{0.1 \\times 0.2}{4}=5 \\mathrm{mH}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40194,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>17</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>18</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p>Magnitude of induced emf&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>At,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>78</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>Current,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#949;</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>78</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40150,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\mu_0 \\pi b^2}{2 a}$","$\\frac{\\mu_o}{2 \\pi} \\cdot \\frac{b^2}{a}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0}{2 \\pi} \\cdot \\frac{a^2}{b}$","$\\frac{\\mu_0 \\pi a^2}{2 b}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\phi=\\mathrm{Mi}=\\mathrm{BA} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{Mi}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\mathrm{i}}{2 \\mathrm{~b}} \\pi \\mathrm{a}^2 \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{M}=\\frac{\\mu_0 \\pi \\mathrm{a}^2}{2 \\mathrm{~b}}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40181,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>According to the Faraday&#39;s law of electromagnetic induction, the emf induced in a conducting loop is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;is time and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;is magnetic flux.</p><p>Here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>&#960;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>&nbsp;(rounded off)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40217,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>L</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>0.25</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>0.025</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mi>H</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>H</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40255,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$(1-\\mathrm{e})$","$\\mathrm{e}$","$\\mathrm{e}^{-1}$","$\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{-1}\\right)$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{i}=\\mathrm{i}_0\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{\\frac{\\mathrm{Rt}}{\\mathrm{L}}}\\right)$\n$=\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{-1}\\right)$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2007","image":null},{"id":40129,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The maximum induced EMF for a rod of length $\\ell$ rotating in a magnetic field $B$ is:<br>$\\varepsilon_{max} = \\frac{B \\omega_{max} \\ell^2}{2} \\quad \\cdots(1)$<br><br>Using energy conservation to find $\\omega_{max}$:<br>$mg\\ell(1 - \\cos 60°) = \\frac{1}{2}(m\\ell^2)\\omega_m^2$<br><br>$\\omega_m = \\sqrt{\\frac{g}{\\ell}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{10}{0.1}} = 10 \\text{ rad/s}$<br><br>From equation (1):<br>$\\varepsilon_{max} = \\frac{2 \\times 10 \\times 0.01}{2} = 0.1 \\text{ V} = 100 \\text{ mV}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null}]